# 🛑 What is CSRF (Cross‑Site Request Forgery)?

**CSRF = attacker tricks a logged‑in user’s browser into sending a request to your server**

Key reason it works:

> **Browsers automatically send cookies with requests**

### Example attack

1.  You are logged into `bank.com`
2.  Bank login uses cookies ✅
3.  You visit `evil.com`
4.  Evil site sends this request:



5.  Browser sends your **bank cookies**
6.  Server thinks **YOU** made the request 😱

***

# ✅ Why CSRF Happens ONLY with Cookies

| Storage      | Auto‑sent by browser | CSRF risk |
| ------------ | -------------------- | --------- |
| Cookies      | ✅ Yes                | ✅ YES     |
| localStorage | ❌ No                 | ❌ NO      |

✅ Cookies need **extra protection**
✅ That protection is **CSRF prevention**

***

# ✅ MAIN CSRF PROTECTION TECHNIQUES (Industry Standard)

| Technique                  | Must use? | Why                               |
| -------------------------- | --------- | --------------------------------- |
| SameSite cookies           | ✅ Yes     | Stops cross‑site cookie sending   |
| CSRF Token (double submit) | ✅ Yes     | Prevents forged requests          |
| Custom headers             | ✅ Yes     | Browsers block cross‑site headers |
| POST/PUT instead of GET    | ✅ Yes     | Avoids link/image attacks         |

✅ **Best practice = SameSite + CSRF token**

***

# 🛡 CSRF Protection Strategy We’ll Implement

### ✅ Industry‑Correct Setup

    Refresh Token → HttpOnly cookie
    CSRF Token    → Normal cookie or response body

### ✅ Validation Rule

> If **cookie exists** AND **CSRF header matches token** → request allowed

